              <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"/>
            </seg>t<seg subtype="vowel" type="component">
              <gap quantity="1" reason="illegible" unit="component"/>
            </seg></p>
          <!-- 
In l14, Pargiter prints [#bha]radvājā sagottra (sic, my [#] reflecting his italics) and notes that we should read sagotrā, which is supposed to agree with bhavanto. Sircar reads (bhā)radvāja-sagottr(ebhyo), showing only unclear but not supplied readings; note also his bhāradvāja as opposed to Pargiter's bharadvājā. I feel Sircar's interpretation makes much more sense (the petitioner's gotra doesn't seem to relevant, but it's still more relevant than that of the officials; also, why would all the officials belong to the same gotra?). However, Pargiter had the plate, while Sircar only had Pargiter's printed rubbing, so I don't think bhyo is there in the original. But perhaps the reading sagottrā as (probably) proposed by Pargiter, may have been meant for an ablative? 
-->
          <!-- 
For ṅkt*m*t* in l15, Pargiter suggests [#aṁśam a]ṅkitum iti. Sircar notes this suggestion and adds his own, [#prasāda]ṅ kartum iti. 
-->
