          <!-- 
In l17 Pargiter emends to nayabhūtes and offers tri-sthala for the next bit. He prints tha as supplied from parallel (italics), but this is clearly not the case. On the facsimile, s is visible; what remains of the subscript letter may be th or a number of other things. I could also imagine ṣṭa. Sircar hazards nayabhūtes to sthūlāvadhāraṇayā or nayabhūti-susthalāvadhāraṇayā. (But stra is very clear and unambiguous in the rubbing.) 
-->
          <!-- 
In l18 Pargiter reads jvana and notes that it could also be śuna, but was probably intended for jana. Sircar reads jñana (sic) and emends to °adhikaraṇika-janān. He also notes that Majumdar (1935-36:156n8) reads this locus as -adhikaraṇaka-jñāN, "those who are acquanted with administrative affairs". 
-->
          <p>sīmā-liṅgāni cāttra<lb n="22"/>pūrvvasyāṁ dhruvilāty-agrahāra sīmā| dakṣiṇasyāṁ karaṅka<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <lb n="23"/>paścimasyāṁ śīlakuṇḍa-grāma sīmā<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> Uttarasyāṁ karaṅka sī<lb break="no" n="24"/>mā<supplied reason="subaudible">.</supplied> <space quantity="4" unit="character"/><!-- 
